es a set of public memory issues concerning the symbolic value of Times Square as threatened public space and the daunting task of commemorating and rebuilding after the attack on the World Trade Center. Focusing on the issue of monumentalization in divergent artistic and media practices, the book demonstrates that the transformation of spatial and temporal experience by memory politics is a major cultural effect of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362030840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503620308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503620308/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles